<!-- ══ 01 EXECUTIVE SUMMARY ══ -->
<section class="section" id="summary">
  <div class="eyebrow"><span class="eyebrow-n">01</span><span class="eyebrow-l">Overview</span></div>
  <h2 class="section-heading">Executive Summary</h2>
  <div class="section-rule"></div>
  <div class="exec-box">
    <p>This proposal covers the integration between <strong>SAP</strong> and <strong>DMS</strong> — specifically the pipeline that polls the SAP API for new manufacturing orders and writes them into the DMS staging table. Two approaches are evaluated: <strong>Option 1 (with AWS SQS)</strong> is recommended for production due to its resilience and zero data loss guarantee. <strong>Option 2 (direct database write)</strong> is suitable for low-volume or development use cases. All downstream processing from the staging table onwards is handled by existing DMS flows and is out of scope for this document.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="kpi-row">
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-v">10 min</div><div class="kpi-l">SAP Poll Interval</div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-v">4 days</div><div class="kpi-l">SQS Message Retention</div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-v">3×</div><div class="kpi-l">Auto Retry Attempts</div></div>
    <div class="kpi"><div class="kpi-v">0</div><div class="kpi-l">Data Loss (With Queue)</div></div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- ══ 02 ARCHITECTURE OPTIONS ══ -->
<section class="section" id="options">
  <div class="eyebrow"><span class="eyebrow-n">02</span><span class="eyebrow-l">Architecture</span></div>
  <h2 class="section-heading">Architecture Options</h2>
  <p class="section-lead">Two approaches are presented for getting SAP orders into the DMS staging table. The choice depends on volume, reliability requirements, and infrastructure constraints.</p>
  <div class="section-rule"></div>
  <div class="opt-cards">
    <div class="opt-card o1">
      <div class="opt-card-hd">
        <div><div class="opt-card-n">Option 1</div><div class="opt-card-nm">With Message Queue (SQS)</div></div>
        <div class="opt-rec">★ Recommended</div>
      </div>
      <div class="opt-card-bd">
        <p class="opt-desc">Integration service polls SAP every 10 minutes and sends new orders to an SQS queue. Lambda is triggered by SQS to read from the queue and write to the DMS staging table. If DMS is unavailable, orders remain safely in the queue until it recovers.</p>
        <div class="opt-path">SAP API → Integration Service → Tracking DB → SQS → Lambda → DMS Staging Table</div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="opt-card o2">
      <div class="opt-card-hd">
        <div><div class="opt-card-n">Option 2</div><div class="opt-card-nm">Direct Database Write</div></div>
        <div class="opt-rec">Dev / Low Volume</div>
      </div>
      <div class="opt-card-bd">
        <p class="opt-desc">Integration service polls SAP every 10 minutes and writes new orders directly into the DMS staging table — no queue involved. Simpler to deploy but permanently loses orders if the database is unavailable at write time. No retry mechanism.</p>
        <div class="opt-path">SAP API → Integration Service → Tracking DB + DMS Staging Table</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h3 class="sub">Decision Matrix</h3>
  <table class="cmp-tbl">
    <thead><tr><th>Criteria</th><th>Option 1 — With SQS ★</th><th>Option 2 — Direct Write</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Daily order volume</td><td>&gt; 100 orders/day</td><td>&lt; 10 orders/day</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Peak hourly load</td><td>&gt; 50 orders/hour</td><td>&lt; 5 orders/hour</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Data loss tolerance</td><td><span class="bg bg-g">Zero tolerance</span></td><td><span class="bg bg-w">Risk acceptable</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Environment</td><td>Production</td><td>Dev / Test / POC</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Network topology</td><td>Separate networks OK</td><td>Same network required</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Failure recovery</td><td><span class="bg bg-g">Automatic</span></td><td><span class="bg bg-r">Manual intervention</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Traffic spike handling</td><td><span class="bg bg-g">Buffered via queue</span></td><td><span class="bg bg-r">DB overload risk</span></td></tr>
      <tr><td>Future growth / multi-client</td><td>Supported</td><td>Not suitable</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</section>

<!-- ══ 03 FLOW DIAGRAMS ══ -->
<section class="section" id="flows">
  <div class="eyebrow"><span class="eyebrow-n">03</span><span class="eyebrow-l">Process Flow</span></div>
  <h2 class="section-heading">Flow Diagrams</h2>
  <p class="section-lead">End-to-end data flow from SAP API polling to DMS staging table write. Downstream processing from the staging table is handled by existing DMS workflows and is not shown.</p>
  <div class="section-rule"></div>

  <!-- OPTION 1 -->
  <div class="flow-wrap fw1">
    <div class="flow-hd"><div class="flow-title">Option 1 — With SQS + Lambda (Recommended)</div><div class="flow-badge">Production</div></div>
    <div class="flow-bd">
      <div class="flow-steps">

        <div class="fstep">
          <div class="sbox">
            <div class="snum">Step 01</div>
            <span class="sicon">🏭</span>
            <div class="stitle">SAP System</div>
            <div class="sdetail">Manufacturing order released and available on SAP API endpoint</div>
            <div class="sbadge">JSON / REST</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="farrow"><div class="aline"></div><div class="ahead"></div><div class="alabel">GET / 10 min</div></div>

        <div class="fstep">
          <div class="sbox">
            <div class="snum">Step 02</div>
            <span class="sicon">⚙️</span>
            <div class="stitle">Integration Service</div>
            <div class="sdetail">Apache Camel polls SAP API, deduplicates against tracking DB, tags each order with client_id</div>
            <div class="sbadge">Dedup Check</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="farrow"><div class="aline"></div><div class="ahead"></div><div class="alabel">Enqueue</div></div>

        <div class="fstep sqs-s">
          <div class="sbox">
            <div class="snum">Step 03</div>
            <span class="sicon">📬</span>
            <div class="stitle">AWS SQS</div>
            <div class="sdetail">Message stored durably for up to 4 days. Auto-retry ×3 on failure. Dead Letter Queue on exhaustion.</div>
            <div class="sbadge">Buffer / 4 days</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="farrow"><div class="aline"></div><div class="ahead"></div><div class="alabel">Trigger</div></div>

        <div class="fstep lmb-s">
          <div class="sbox">
            <div class="snum">Step 04</div>
            <span class="sicon">λ</span>
            <div class="stitle">AWS Lambda</div>
            <div class="sdetail">Triggered by SQS. Reads up to 10 messages, writes each to DMS staging table, deletes message on success</div>
            <div class="sbadge">Serverless</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="farrow"><div class="aline"></div><div class="ahead"></div><div class="alabel">INSERT</div></div>

        <div class="fstep end-s">
          <div class="sbox">
            <div class="snum">Step 05</div>
            <span class="sicon">🗄️</span>
            <div class="stitle">DMS Staging Table</div>
            <div class="sdetail">Order row written with status PENDING. Existing DMS jobs pick up from here.</div>
            <div class="sbadge">✓ Handed Off</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
      <div class="flow-notes">
        <div class="fnote pos"><strong>Zero Data Loss</strong><span>If DMS database is offline, messages remain safely in SQS. Lambda retries automatically once the database is back — no manual recovery required.</span></div>
        <div class="fnote inf"><strong>Lambda Triggered by SQS</strong><span>Lambda is directly triggered by SQS — as messages arrive in the queue, Lambda automatically picks them up and writes to the DMS staging table. Fully managed and serverless.</span></div>
        <div class="fnote pos"><strong>Traffic Spike Handling</strong><span>Any volume of orders (e.g. 2,000 at month-end) are enqueued instantly. Lambda drains the queue steadily without stressing the database connection pool.</span></div>
        <div class="fnote inf"><strong>Auto Retry on Failure</strong><span>Failed Lambda writes return the message to the queue (up to 3 retries). After 3 failures the message is moved to a Dead Letter Queue for investigation.</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- OPTION 2 -->
  <div class="flow-wrap fw2">
    <div class="flow-hd"><div class="flow-title">Option 2 — Direct Database Write</div><div class="flow-badge">Dev / Low Volume</div></div>
    <div class="flow-bd">
      <div class="flow-steps">

        <div class="fstep">
          <div class="sbox">
            <div class="snum">Step 01</div>
            <span class="sicon">🏭</span>
            <div class="stitle">SAP System</div>
            <div class="sdetail">Manufacturing order released and available on SAP API endpoint</div>
            <div class="sbadge">JSON / REST</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="farrow"><div class="aline"></div><div class="ahead"></div><div class="alabel">GET / 10 min</div></div>

        <div class="fstep">
          <div class="sbox">
            <div class="snum">Step 02</div>
            <span class="sicon">⚙️</span>
            <div class="stitle">Integration Service</div>
            <div class="sdetail">Polls SAP API, deduplicates against tracking DB, writes directly to DMS staging — no queue</div>
            <div class="sbadge">Direct Write</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="farrow"><div class="aline"></div><div class="ahead"></div><div class="alabel">INSERT</div></div>

        <div class="fstep end-s">
          <div class="sbox">
            <div class="snum">Step 03</div>
            <span class="sicon">🗄️</span>
            <div class="stitle">DMS Staging Table</div>
            <div class="sdetail">Order row written immediately with status PENDING. Existing DMS jobs pick up from here.</div>
            <div class="sbadge">✓ Handed Off</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
      <div class="flow-notes">
        <div class="fnote pos"><strong>Simpler Architecture</strong><span>Fewer components — no SQS, no Lambda. Easier initial deployment. Both servers must be on the same network with direct DB access.</span></div>
        <div class="fnote cau"><strong>Faster Under Normal Conditions</strong><span>Orders appear in the staging table within the 10-minute poll cycle, without any queue processing delay.</span></div>
        <div class="fnote neg"><strong>No Recovery Mechanism</strong><span>If DMS database is unreachable at write time, the order is permanently lost. There is no queue, no retry, and no automatic recovery.</span></div>
        <div class="fnote neg"><strong>Traffic Spike Risk</strong><span>A large batch of simultaneous orders can exhaust the DB connection pool, causing partial silent data loss with no automated fallback.</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

